ng a ticket","body":"<h2>Penalty Charge Notices issued by local councils</h2>\n\n<p>The cost of a Penalty Charge Notice (<abbr title=\"Penalty Charge Notice\">PCN</abbr>) parking ticket goes up the longer you don&rsquo;t <a href=\"/pay-parking-fine\" title=\"Pay a parking fine\">pay it:</a> </p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>If you pay within 14 days, the penalty charge is reduced by 50% (or 21 days if your car was caught on camera and the <abbr title=\"Penalty Charge Notice\">PCN</abbr> is posted to you).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If you pay after 14 days but within 28 days you pay the full amount.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If you don’t pay within 28 days, the council will send you a reminder (called a ‘Notice to Owner’).</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If you don’t pay within 28 days of getting the reminder, the council may increase the penalty charge by 50%.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you think the ticket is wrong, you can <a href=\"challenging-a-ticket\" title=\"Parking tickets: How to appeal\">challenge</a> it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> A £60 <abbr title=\"Penalty Charge Notice\">PCN</abbr> will cost you £30 if paid within 14 days, £60 if paid within 56 days, and up to £90 if paid after 56 days.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Fixed Penalty Notice (<abbr title=\"Fixed Penalty Notice\">FPN</abbr>)</h2>\n<p>You have 28 days to pay an <abbr title=\"Fixed Penalty Notice\">FPN</abbr> or ask for a hearing in court if you want to <a href=\"challenging-a-ticket\" title=\"Parking tickets: appealing\">appeal</a> it. After this, the fine increases by 50%.</p>\n\n<p>If you pay the fine, you won’t be prosecuted and no record of your offence will be kept.</p>\n\n<p>If you ignore it, you’ll receive a court summons.</p>\n\n<h2>Excess or Standard Charge Notice (<abbr title=\"Excess Charge Notice\">ECN</abbr> or <abbr title=\"Standard Charge Notice\">SCN</abbr>)</h2>\n<p>You usually have 28 days to pay these. In most cases, the fine is reduced by 50% if you pay it within 14 days.</p>\n\n<h2>Ways to pay</h2>\n<p>These are usually listed on the ticket. The main ways are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/pay-parking-fine\" title=\"Pay a parking fine\">online</a> </li>\n  <li>by credit or debit card over the phone</li>\n  <li>in person at your council’s customer service offices</li>\n  <li>by cheque or postal order</li>\n</ul>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/parking-tickets/challenging-a-ticket","slug":"challenging-a-ticket","order":3,"title":"Challenging a ticket","body":"<h2>Penalty Charge Notice (<abbr title=\"Penalty Charge Notice\">PCN</abbr>)</h2>\n<p>If you think the ticket is wrong, you can challenge it:</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>If you challenge it within 28 days, this is called an ‘informal challenge’. You need to write to your council or <a href=\"/appeal-parking-fine\" title=\"Appeal a parking fine\">challenge it online</a>. If you challenge it within 14 days, and the council turns you down, the council may give you more time to pay only 50% of the penalty charge.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If the council sends you a ‘Notice to Owner’, you can challenge it. This is called a ‘formal challenge’.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>The council has 56 days to consider your formal challenge.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If the council agrees with you, it will cancel the fine. If it turns your challenge down, it will send you a ‘Notice of Rejection’.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>If you disagree with the ‘Notice of Rejection’, you have 28 days to appeal.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>You can appeal to the:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.trafficpenaltytribunal.gov.uk/site/index.php\" title=\"Traffic Penalty Tribunal\">Traffic Penalty Tribunal</a> for <abbr title=\"Penalty Charge Notices\">PCNs</abbr> issued in England (outside London)</li>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.patas.gov.uk/default.htm\" title=\"Parking and Traffic Appeals Service\">Parking and Traffic Appeals service</a> for <abbr title=\"Penalty Charge Notices\">PCNs</abbr> issued in 